SIMPLE: emphasis
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: emphasis
<hw>em"pha*sis</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧m"f⟦adot⟧*s⟦icr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Emphases</plw>
<pr>(⟦ecr⟧m"f⟦adot⟧*s⟦emac⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr.
<grk>'e`mfasis</grk> significance, force of expression, fr.
<grk>'emfai`nein</grk> to show in, indicate; <grk>'en</grk> in +
<grk>fai`nein</grk> to show. See <er>In</er>, and <er>Phase</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>A particular stress of utterance, or
force of voice, given in reading and speaking to one or more words whose
signification the speaker intends to impress specially upon his
audience.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The province of <qex>emphasis</qex> is so much more important than
accent, that the customary seat of the latter is changed, when the
claims of <qex>emphasis</qex> require it.</q> <rj><qau>E.
Porter.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A peculiar impressiveness of expression or weight of
thought; vivid representation, enforcing assent; <as>as, to dwell on a
subject with great <ex>emphasis</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>External objects stand before us . . . in all the life and
<qex>emphasis</qex> of extension, figure, and color.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>a special attention given to, or extra importance
attached to, something; <as>as, a guided tour of Egypt with
<ex>emphasis</ex> on the monuments along the Nile</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>something to which great importance is attached;
<as>as, the need for increased spending on education was the
<ex>emphasis</ex> of his speech</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>emphasise</ent>⟦br⟧
